          "body": "Verses 10-17 constitute Qohelet's most sustained meditation on wealth's failure, and he delivers it through three successive portraits rather than abstract argument. The first portrait (5:10-11) is structural: the love of money is constitutionally incapable of producing satisfaction because desire and its object are mismatched — more money produces more appetite and more dependents, and the owner's advantage shrinks to merely watching. The second portrait (5:12) is phenomenological: the laborer sleeps well regardless of what he eats; the rich man's abundance prevents sleep. Wealth promised rest from labor; it delivers insomnia. The third portrait (5:13-17) is biographical and devastating: the man who hoards wealth 'to his hurt' loses it through a bad investment, fathers a son he cannot support, departs the world as naked as he arrived, and spends his days eating in darkness with 'great vexation, sickness and anger' (5:17). The repeated phrase 'grievous evil' (chalah ra, 5:13, 16) signals Qohelet's controlled moral indignation — this is not merely unfortunate, it is a sick distortion of the way things should go. The summary verdict is surgical: 'So what is the advantage to him who toils for the wind?' (5:16). The wind-image recurs from 1:14 and 2:11 — effort that disappears without leaving a trace."
