          "body": "After five chapters of largely negative cataloguing, Ecclesiastes 5:18-20 delivers the most theologically dense positive statement in the book's first half. Qohelet calls it 'good and fitting' (tov ve-yapheh) to eat, drink, and enjoy one's labor during the few years God has given — 'for this is his reward' (5:18). The word 'reward' (cheleq, lot/portion) is significant: enjoyment is not something the laborer wrests from the system by clever management but something assigned to him as his divinely apportioned share. Verse 19 makes the theology explicit: God gives riches and wealth, and He also gives the capacity to enjoy them — both the goods and the ability to receive them gladly are gifts (mattat) from God. This is not prosperity theology, which asserts that God must give wealth to the faithful; it is gift theology, which asserts that whatever God has given — much or little — can be received as His good gift if the receiver has been given the further gift of a grateful heart. The chapter closes with a quietly astonishing statement: the person kept occupied by God-given gladness 'will not often consider the years of his life' (5:20). Where the hoarder ate his days in darkness counting what he had lost, the joyful person is too absorbed in present gladness to fixate on time's passage. This is not escapism but the fruit of fear: the one who has rightly oriented himself to the God who is in heaven finds that God himself occupies the heart with joy."
