        "number": 1,
        "title": "Guarding the approach — why religious busyness becomes foolishness",
        "range": "5:1-3",
        "excerpt": "Guard your steps as you go to the house of God and draw near to listen rather than to offer the sacrifice of fools; for they do not know they are doing evil.",
        "body": "The opening imperative — 'Guard your steps' — places the reader at the threshold of the Jerusalem temple and immediately reframes what the greatest danger there is. The naive reader might expect Qohelet to warn against staying away, or against overt sacrilege. Instead he warns against the sacrifice of fools, which is a sacrifice that looks identical to genuine worship from the outside. The fool brings an offering, performs the rite, and goes away — and never notices that he has been doing evil. The self-deception is total.\n\nThe mechanism Qohelet names is listening. The contrast is not between sacrifice and prayer but between offering and listening — between approaching God with something to give and approaching God to receive what He says. This is the Deuteronomic tradition concentrated: 'Hear, O Israel' (Deuteronomy 6:4) precedes all commandment. The failure of the fool is not liturgical but postureal — he has come to perform rather than to receive. Tim Keller's observation is apt here: religious performance is one of the most effective ways to avoid genuine encounter with God, precisely because it uses the forms of encounter as a substitute for the substance.\n\nVerse 3 deploys a comparative proverb to explain the dynamic: dreams come from too much anxious effort; the fool's voice comes from too many words. The connection is physiological and psychological — Qohelet's audience would recognize the relationship between an overworked, anxious mind and incoherent night-dreaming. The fool's many words in the worship context are the verbal equivalent of that mental noise: output that exceeds intake, speech that substitutes for listening.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Shamar* (guard) is the watchman's term — active, vigilant attention. *Kesil* (fool) in wisdom literature is not the intellectually simple (*peti*) but the morally and spiritually obtuse — the one who acts as if God is not there or does not notice. *Zevach* (sacrifice) is the general term for animal sacrifice, the offering requiring maximum investment from the worshipper — and yet even this can be foolish if the heart is absent."
